    "reasoning": "Let me also calculate some legacy provider comparisons:\n\n- ULA Delta IV Heavy: ~$400M / 28,790 kg = ~$13,893/kg\n- ULA Atlas V: ~$100-150M / 18,850 kg = ~$5,305-$7,958/kg\n- ULA Vulcan Centaur: ~$100M / 27,400 kg = ~$3,650/kg\n- Ariane 5: ~$170M / 20,000 kg = ~$8,500/kg\n- Falcon 9 (list, reusable): ~$67M / 15,600 kg = ~$4,295/kg\n- Falcon 9 (list, expendable): ~$67M / 22,800 kg = ~$2,939/kg\n- Falcon Heavy: ~$97M / 63,800 kg = ~$1,520/kg\n\nLet me also calculate the implied number of customer launches. If customer mass is 312 metric tons and the filing says average capacity per mission is 13 metric tons:\n- If all customer launches were at full capacity: 312 / 13 = 24 launches\n- But customers rarely fill full capacity. PayloadSpace says average customer payload is 3,370 kg.\n- If average customer payload is 3,370 kg: 312,000 / 3,370 = ~93 launches\n\nBut 93 customer launches out of 170 total seems high. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, the filing says 165 Falcon 9 rockets were launched in 2025, and 170 total missions (including Starship). The internal mass was 1,901 metric tons. If Starlink satellites are about 260 kg each (V1.5) or 800 kg (V2 Mini), and they launch ~20-25 per Falcon 9 mission...\n\nActually, let me not try to estimate the exact number of customer launches. The key point is that the filing doesn't disclose this number, which is itself a disclosure gap.\n\nLet me now write the comprehensive answer.",
